_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H13N3O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-ureidopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"citrulline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H2,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H14N4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"arginine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C8H19N3O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"alanylornithine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Orn-Ala/ornithine-containing dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C9H21N5O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"alanylarginine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Arg-Ala/arginine-containing dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 adsorption followed by Fe-S mediated hydrogenation to formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-S minerals such as greigite and mackinawite are established catalysts for vent-like CO2 reduction to C1 products under serpentinization-driven, anoxic conditions; this provides shared reduced carbon feedstock for downstream protometabolism (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate formation from reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent setting with redox and pH gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise C1 fixation and reductive carbon-carbon assembly on iron mineral surfaces generate alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies pyruvate as plausibly formed at hydrothermal vents and central to vent protometabolism; iron oxide/sulfide minerals are implicated in reductive carbon fixation networks yielding keto acids (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent fluid; mineral-surface mediated reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly notes that pyruvate in vent simulations undergoes reductive amination to amino acids. Mineral-surface Fe/S catalysis makes alanine a realistic donor for later transamination-like biochemical exchanges (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic Cu(I)-mediated coupling of acetylene and HCN to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite analog support)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) photoredox-compatible surface setting with mineral support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow illuminated surface/shoreline environment; anoxic; literature-critical Cu(I) cross-coupling chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu(I)-mediated C-C bond formation between acetylene and HCN yields acrylonitrile as the C3 nitrile scaffold.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies acrylonitrile production from acetylene and HCN as the first committed step in the Sutherland-group arginine route, specifically via Cu(I)-catalyzed cross-coupling in a cyanosulfidic setting (Patel et al., 2015). Surface minerals are included here as geochemical supports/localizers to satisfy network requirements, but Cu(I) remains the literature-critical catalyst.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile forming beta-aminopropionitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surface concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous pool; Michael-type NH3 addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic conjugate addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile yields beta-aminopropionitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report lists ammonia addition to acrylonitrile as the next established step of the prebiotic arginine sequence. Clay and sulfide surfaces are plausible concentrators in evaporitic or shallow vent-associated pools (Patel et al., 2015; Powner, Sutherland & Szostak, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidinylation of beta-aminopropionitrile by cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none intrinsic; mineral concentration surfaces present\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly alkaline, anoxic solution; known to be incomplete and mixture-forming\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Primary amine attacks electrophilic carbon of cyanamide, introducing the guanidino-equivalent functionality on the 3-carbon nitrile scaffold.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly identifies cyanamide guanidinylation of beta-aminopropionitrile as a key but imperfect step in the selective prebiotic route to arginine. Cyanamide is singled out as a universal prebiotic reagent in systems chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoredox reduction and aldehyde trapping to hemiaminal 37\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV with mineral-supported photochemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; oxygen-free; H2S present; aldehyde trapped extraordinarily efficiently by residual cyanamide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/Cu photoreduction converts the nitrile-side-chain intermediate toward beta-aminopropionaldehyde chemistry, which is immediately trapped by cyanamide as a stable hemiaminal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The identification of stable hemiaminal intermediate 37 formed by reaction of beta-aminopropionaldehyde with residual cyanamide is highlighted in the report as a critical selectivity-enhancing discovery. UV-driven Cu photoredox in the presence of H2S is central to the Sutherland framework (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Dark cyanohydrin formation from the trapped aldehyde intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-enabled concentration/stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dark reaction; anoxic; HCN addition analogous to Kiliani-Fischer homologation logic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to the trapped aldehydic center yields a cyanohydrin intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that after hemiaminal formation, a dark reaction with HCN generates the cyanohydrin intermediate, extending the chain in a Kiliani-Fischer-like homologation sequence (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfidolysis of cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxythioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S-driven sulfidolysis on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur incorporation converts the cyanohydrin-derived intermediate into an alpha-hydroxythioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research explicitly lists sulfidolysis of the cyanohydrin by H2S as the next stage, producing an alpha-hydroxythioamide in the arginine precursor sequence (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"UV deoxygenation and final photoredox amination to arginine alpha-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox-compatible UV surface chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; anoxic; deoxygenation to thioamide followed by photoreduction and addition of HCN/NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation deoxygenates the alpha-hydroxythioamide to a thioamide, which under further photoreductive processing and HCN/NH3 addition yields the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report directly describes UV deoxygenation of the alpha-hydroxythioamide to a thioamide, followed by further photoreduction plus HCN/NH3 to produce the arginine alpha-aminonitrile. This is the key terminal step of the Sutherland-style prebiotic route (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of arginine alpha-aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool or geothermal cycling; nitrile hydrolysis during aqueous aging\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile into the corresponding alpha-amino acid arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"While the report emphasizes formation of the arginine alpha-aminonitrile as the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic endpoint, hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard completion step in Strecker-like and cyanosulfidic amino-acid chemistry; this connection is necessary to complete the arginine network and is chemically conservative (Strecker, 1850; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine formation from HCN-derived prebiotic chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration and photochemical surface assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich solution / spark-photochemical analogue; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Network-level HCN oligomerization/hydrolysis/reductive amination chemistry yields ornithine as a more accessible basic amino acid than arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states ornithine is more prebiotically accessible than arginine and has been identified in HCN solutions and spark-discharge experiments, motivating its inclusion as an alternate precursor/basic residue reservoir. This reaction is summarized as a network condensation of those findings rather than a single-step laboratory transformation (Miller, 1953 reanalyses summarized by Parker et al., 2011; Longo et al., 2013; as discussed in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Abiotic guanidination of free ornithine to arginine by cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"room temperature; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; selective guanidination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Side-chain primary amine of ornithine attacks cyanamide carbon, forming the guanidino group and yielding arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly describes aqueous room-temperature post-synthetic guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide under neutral to slightly alkaline conditions, and identifies this as a plausible route for arginine emergence from simpler basic amino acids (Longo et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic interconversion of ornithine and citrulline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool; carbamoyl-type chemistry as protometabolic urea-cycle analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbamoylation-like modification of ornithine yields citrulline as a urea-cycle-related intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights citrulline as a key intermediate structurally linking ornithine and arginine in a plausible protometabolic urea-cycle-like network. This step is included to represent that literature-supported interconversion motif, though detailed prebiotic conditions remain less resolved than the cyanamide guanidination route (as discussed in the report; speculative but literature-motivated).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry peptide formation of alanine and ornithine to an ornithine-containing dipeptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal wet-dry cycles; condensation-dehydration in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Repeated dry-down concentrates amino acids and drives condensation to a simple ornithine-containing peptide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes that volcanic hot springs and dry-down conditions promote peptide formation, and that early statistical polypeptides likely incorporated ornithine as a basic residue before arginine became established. This reaction bridges hydrothermal amino-acid production with the peptide-first ornithine model (Forsythe et al., 2015; Longo et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Post-synthetic guanidination of an ornithine-containing peptide to an arginine-containing peptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"room temperature aqueous solution; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; statistical conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The ornithine side chain within the peptide undergoes selective guanidination by cyanamide, generating an arginine residue in situ.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically emphasizes that ornithine side chains within polypeptides can be converted statistically and selectively into arginine by cyanamide in aqueous solution, improving folding and nucleic-acid binding. This is one of the strongest literature-supported alternative routes for arginine emergence (Longo et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic release of arginine from arginine-containing peptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"partial hydrolysis during aqueous cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Peptide bond hydrolysis releases free arginine along with alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is a necessary network connector showing how post-synthetically guanidinated peptides could feed a free-arginine pool under prebiotic aqueous cycling. It is chemically straightforward though not singled out experimentally in the report, so it is included as a conservative bridging step (Longo et al., 2020; speculative connector).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic route from atmospheric HCN and acetylene\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct literature-grounded Sutherland-type surface route from HCN and acetylene to arginine via acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, guanidinated intermediate, hemiaminal trapping, cyanohydrin/thioamide chemistry, alpha-aminonitrile, then hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-ammonia-fed cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"As P1, but ammonia is supplied by hydrothermal environments, explicitly linking vent chemistry to the surface arginine synthesis sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-H2S-fed cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface arginine homologation sequence driven by hydrothermal delivery of H2S into shallow photoredox pools.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-shallow vent integrated arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Full integrated story in which hydrothermal carbon reduction establishes a shared reduced geochemical context and exports ammonia/H2S into a shallow illuminated vent/pool where the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway proceeds.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Free ornithine to arginine by cyanamide\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative literature-supported emergence route in which the more accessible basic amino acid ornithine is formed in HCN chemistry and subsequently guanidinated by cyanamide to yield arginine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine-containing peptide then post-synthetic arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal alanine and surface ornithine are joined by wet-dry peptide formation; peptide-bound ornithine is then selectively guanidinated by cyanamide and hydrolyzed to release free arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Citrulline-branch protometabolic arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Protometabolic route in which ornithine enters a urea-cycle-like intermediate pool as citrulline before converging on arginine chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only cyanosulfidic to aminonitrile with delayed hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"A variant emphasizing accumulation of arginine alpha-aminonitrile in surface pools before later biochemical hydrolysis to arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-peptide-first-to-arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"A peptide-first variant where hydrothermal alanine enters statistical peptides with ornithine, followed by cyanamide guanidination to create arginine residues and eventual free arginine release.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_023\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence route through ornithine and cyanosulfidic arginine precursor pools\",\n      \"description\": \"A mixed network route in which both arginine alpha-aminonitrile and ornithine are generated in parallel geochemical modules, any of which can supply the final arginine pool through hydrolysis or guanidination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_021\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_019\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-guided view that prebiotic arginine arose primarily through a cyanosulfidic, Cu-photoredox homologation sequence beginning from HCN and acetylene in shallow illuminated surface/vent settings, while hydrothermal chemistry supplies shared C1/C3 feedstocks and amino-acid precursors, and biochemical/prebiotic stages convert arginine precursors or ornithine-containing peptides into arginine by abiotic guanidination. The network therefore combines: (i) hydrothermal generation of formate, pyruvate, alanine, and ammonia-bearing feedstocks; (ii) surface cyanosulfidic assembly of the arginine carbon skeleton through acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, guanidinated intermediates, hemiaminal trapping, cyanohydrin/thioamide chemistry, and alpha-aminonitrile formation; and (iii) final hydrolysis or post-synthetic ornithine guanidination in prebiotic pools/peptides to yield arginine. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as different valid traversals through these shared hubs and environmental transfers.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environm