ate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "beta-aminopropionitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,4H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8N4", "iupac_name": "3-guanidinopropanenitrile", "common_name": "guanidinated beta-aminopropionitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H10N4O", "iupac_name": "hemiaminal intermediate of beta-aminopropionaldehyde and cyanamide", "common_name": "hemiaminal 37", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H10N5O", "iupac_name": "cyanohydrin intermediate of the trapped guanidino aldehyde", "common_name": "arginine-path cyanohydrin intermediate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H11N5OS", "iupac_name": "alpha-hydroxythioamide intermediate", "common_name": "alpha-hydroxythioamide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H11N5S", "iupac_name": "thioamide intermediate in arginine homologation", "common_name": "arginine-path thioamide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C6H13N5", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-guanidinopentanenitrile", "common_name": "arginine alpha-aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H13N3O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-ureidopentanoic acid", "common_name": "citrulline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(6(11)12)2-1-3-9-5(8)10/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H2,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-guanidinopentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C8H19N3O3", "iupac_name": "alanylornithine", "common_name": "Orn-Ala/ornithine-containing dipeptide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C9H21N5O3", "iupac_name": "alanylarginine", "common_name": "Arg-Ala/arginine-containing dipeptide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich serpentinization setting"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface CO2 adsorption followed by Fe-S mediated hydrogenation to formate.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-S minerals such as greigite and mackinawite are established catalysts for vent-like CO2 reduction to C1 products under serpentinization-driven, anoxic conditions; this provides shared reduced carbon feedstock for downstream protometabolism (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate formation from reduced carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent setting with redox and pH gradients"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise C1 fixation and reductive carbon-carbon assembly on iron mineral surfaces generate alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies pyruvate as plausibly formed at hydrothermal vents and central to vent protometabolism; iron oxide/sulfide minerals are implicated in reductive carbon fixation networks yielding keto acids (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent fluid; mineral-surface mediated reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "The deep research explicitly notes that pyruvate in vent simulations undergoes reductive amination to amino acids. Mineral-surface Fe/S catalysis makes alanine a realistic donor for later transamination-like biochemical exchanges (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cyanosulfidic Cu(I)-mediated coupling of acetylene and HCN to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite analog support)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) photoredox-compatible surface setting with mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow illuminated surface/shoreline environment; anoxic; literature-critical Cu(I) cross-coupling chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Cu(I)-mediated C-C bond formation between acetylene and HCN yields acrylonitrile as the C3 nitrile scaffold.", "reasoning": "The report identifies acrylonitrile production from acetylene and HCN as the first committed step in the Sutherland-group arginine route, specifically via Cu(I)-catalyzed cross-coupling in a cyanosulfidic setting (Patel et al., 2015). Surface minerals are included here as geochemical supports/localizers to satisfy network requirements, but Cu(I) remains the literature-critical catalyst."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile forming beta-aminopropionitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous pool; Michael-type NH3 addition"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic conjugate addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile yields beta-aminopropionitrile.", "reasoning": "The research report lists ammonia addition to acrylonitrile as the next established step of the prebiotic arginine sequence. Clay and sulfide surfaces are plausible concentrators in evaporitic or shallow vent-associated pools (Patel et al., 2015; Powner, Sutherland & Szostak, 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Guanidinylation of beta-aminopropionitrile by cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none intrinsic; mineral concentration surfaces present", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly alkaline, anoxic solution; known to be incomplete and mixture-forming"}, "mechanism": "Primary amine attacks electrophilic carbon of cyanamide, introducing the guanidino-equivalent functionality on the 3-carbon nitrile scaffold.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies cyanamide guanidinylation of beta-aminopropionitrile as a key but imperfect step in the selective prebiotic route to arginine. Cyanamide is singled out as a universal prebiotic reagent in systems chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Photoredox reduction and aldehyde trapping to hemiaminal 37", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV with mineral-supported photochemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; oxygen-free; H2S present; aldehyde trapped extraordinarily efficiently by residual cyanamide"}, "mechanism": "UV/Cu photoreduction converts the nitrile-side-chain intermediate toward beta-aminopropionaldehyde chemistry, which is immediately trapped by cyanamide as a stable hemiaminal.", "reasoning": "The identification of stable hemiaminal intermediate 37 formed by reaction of beta-aminopropionaldehyde with residual cyanamide is highlighted in the report as a critical selectivity-enhancing discovery. UV-driven Cu photoredox in the presence of H2S is central to the Sutherland framework (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Dark cyanohydrin formation from the trapped aldehyde intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-enabled concentration/stabilization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dark reaction; anoxic; HCN addition analogous to Kiliani-Fischer homologation logic"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic cyanide addition to the trapped aldehydic center yields a cyanohydrin intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report states that after hemiaminal for