rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of arginine alpha-aminonitrile to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool or geothermal cycling; nitrile hydrolysis during aqueous aging"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile into the corresponding alpha-amino acid arginine.", "reasoning": "While the report emphasizes formation of the arginine alpha-aminonitrile as the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic endpoint, hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard completion step in Strecker-like and cyanosulfidic amino-acid chemistry; this connection is necessary to complete the arginine network and is chemically conservative (Strecker, 1850; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ornithine formation from HCN-derived prebiotic chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration and photochemical surface assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich solution / spark-photochemical analogue; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Network-level HCN oligomerization/hydrolysis/reductive amination chemistry yields ornithine as a more accessible basic amino acid than arginine.", "reasoning": "The report states ornithine is more prebiotically accessible than arginine and has been identified in HCN solutions and spark-discharge experiments, motivating its inclusion as an alternate precursor/basic residue reservoir. This reaction is summarized as a network condensation of those findings rather than a single-step laboratory transformation (Miller, 1953 reanalyses summarized by Parker et al., 2011; Longo et al., 2013; as discussed in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Abiotic guanidination of free ornithine to arginine by cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "room temperature; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; selective guanidination"}, "mechanism": "Side-chain primary amine of ornithine attacks cyanamide carbon, forming the guanidino group and yielding arginine.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly describes aqueous room-temperature post-synthetic guanidination of ornithine by cyanamide under neutral to slightly alkaline conditions, and identifies this as a plausible route for arginine emergence from simpler basic amino acids (Longo et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Protometabolic interconversion of ornithine and citrulline", "inputs": ["mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "prebiotic pool; carbamoyl-type chemistry as protometabolic urea-cycle analog"}, "mechanism": "Carbamoylation-like modification of ornithine yields citrulline as a urea-cycle-related intermediate.", "reasoning": "The report highlights citrulline as a key intermediate structurally linking ornithine and arginine in a plausible protometabolic urea-cycle-like network. This step is included to represent that literature-supported interconversion motif, though detailed prebiotic conditions remain less resolved than the cyanamide guanidination route (as discussed in the report; speculative but literature-motivated)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Wet-dry peptide formation of alanine and ornithine to an ornithine-containing dipeptide", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "geothermal wet-dry cycles; condensation-dehydration in prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Repeated dry-down concentrates amino acids and drives condensation to a simple ornithine-containing peptide.", "reasoning": "The report notes that volcanic hot springs and dry-down conditions promote peptide formation, and that early statistical polypeptides likely incorporated ornithine as a basic residue before arginine became established. This reaction bridges hydrothermal amino-acid production with the peptide-first ornithine model (Forsythe et al., 2015; Longo et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Post-synthetic guanidination of an ornithine-containing peptide to an arginine-containing peptide", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "room temperature aqueous solution; neutral to slightly alkaline pH; statistical conversion"}, "mechanism": "The ornithine side chain within the peptide undergoes selective guanidination by cyanamide, generating an arginine residue in situ.", "reasoning": "The report specifically emphasizes that ornithine side chains within polypeptides can be converted statistically and selectively into arginine by cyanamide in aqueous solution, improving folding and nucleic-acid binding. This is one of the strongest literature-supported alternative routes for arginine emergence (Longo et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrolytic release of arginine from arginine-containing peptide", "inputs": ["mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "partial hydrolysis during aqueous cycling"}, "mechanism": "Peptide bond hydrolysis releases free arginine along with alanine.", "reasoning": "This