neral-surface mediated CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S phases gives reduced one-carbon product formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported by hydrothermal vent Fe-S catalysis literature summarized in the report, where greigite and related minerals mediate CO2 reduction under alkaline vent conditions; this step provides connected reduced-carbon feedstock without asserting unsupported direct arginine synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Martin, 2004; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor to alkaline vent setting; anoxic; connected to serpentinization-derived H2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and reduction assemble a three-carbon alpha-keto acid pool represented by pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly notes pyruvate as plausibly formed at vents and central to downstream amino-acid chemistry. This network therefore uses pyruvate as a hydrothermal hub but keeps the step generalized and conservative rather than over-specified beyond the research summary (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent interface; mineral-surface reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes mineral-assisted imine formation with ammonia followed by reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report specifically identifies pyruvate reactivity and reductive amination to amino acids under vent conditions as experimentally supported. This creates a hydrothermal-to-biochemical connection without relying on unsupported ornithine synthesis (Barge et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Cu-photoredox coupling of acetylene and HCN to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) photoredox with mineral-supported surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow geothermal or intertidal setting; anoxic; Cu(I) required per literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu(I)-mediated C-C cross-coupling of acetylene with HCN forms acrylonitrile; mineral surfaces act as concentrating/photochemical supports.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the first committed arginine-specific step in the literature-supported cyanosulfidic route. The report explicitly identifies Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of acetylene and HCN to acrylonitrile as the entry to the three-carbon tether (Patel et al., 2015). TiO2 and sulfide minerals are included as required surface mineral agents and as plausible supports in UV-exposed sulfidic settings, but Cu(I) remains the decisive catalytic species.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface ammonia addition to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration; no unique catalyst required beyond surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or geothermal pool; anoxic; NH3 addition to activated nitrile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic conjugate addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile gives beta-aminopropionitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies ammonia addition to acrylonitrile as the next step after Cu-coupling. Mineral agents are included to satisfy the required surface-mineral specification and to reflect plausible concentration on clays/sulfide surfaces in cyanosulfidic systems (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface guanidinylation of beta-aminopropionitrile by cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on clay/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly alkaline; incomplete conversion reported; cyanosulfidic network context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amine of beta-aminopropionitrile attacks the electrophilic carbon of cyanamide to form a guanidinated nitrile derivative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly states that beta-aminopropionitrile is treated with cyanamide to produce a guanidinated derivative, while also emphasizing that direct guanidinylation is relatively inefficient and leaves mixed material. That inefficiency is preserved here rather than hidden (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoredox reduction and cyanamide trapping to hemiaminal 37\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with UV and H2S; mineral-supported irradiated surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV; oxygen-free; residual cyanamide traps beta-aminopropionaldehyde as stable hemiaminal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoreduction under Cu redox cycling and H2S generates the corresponding aldehyde equivalent, which is trapped extraordinarily efficiently by cyanamide to give stable hemiaminal 37.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the report closely: UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox chemistry in the presence of H2S leads to aldehyde generation and cyanamide trapping, with hemiaminal 37 identified as a key stabilizing intermediate. This trapping is essential because free aldehydes would otherwise be too reactive in complex mixtures (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface dark cyanohydrin formation from hemiaminal 37\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on clay/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dark reaction; anoxic; HCN addition in pooled solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN adds to the aldehydic/hemiaminal carbon center to generate a cyanohydrin intermediate in a Kiliani-Fischer-like homologation sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly describes a dark reaction with HCN converting hemiaminal 37 into a cyanohydrin intermediate. Mineral agents are included as plausible concentrating surfaces in evaporitic or geothermal pools (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sulfidolysis of cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxythioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfidolysis in sulfidic surface environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; H2S-rich volcanic/geothermal pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfide substitutes into the cyanohydrin-derived intermediate to produce an alpha-hydroxythioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is directly stated in the report: addition of H2S to the cyanohydrin produces an alpha-hydroxythioamide. Sulfide minerals are explicitly appropriate for cyanide/sulfide surface chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV deoxygenation of alpha-hydroxythioamide to thioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation; Cu photoredox-compatible surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic photochemical deoxygenation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation drives deoxygenation of the alpha-hydroxythioamide to the corresponding thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies UV irradiation of the alpha-hydroxythioamide as causing deoxygenation to yield a thioamide. This is a core part of the Patel et al. systems chemistry homologation sequence (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoreduction and final amination to arginine alpha-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox in H2S-rich setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"oxygen-free; further photoreduction followed by HCN and NH3 addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoreduction of the thioamide followed by cyanide incorporation and amination forms the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly concludes the cyanosulfidic sequence with further photoreduction of the thioamide followed by HCN and NH3 addition, producing the arginine alpha-aminonitrile precursor. This is the most direct literature-supported prebiotic precursor to free arginine in the supplied research (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of arginine alpha-aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling or standing pools; step is chemically expected but less directly documented than precursor formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to amino acids is chemically standard and necessary to connect the literature-supported arginine alpha-aminonitrile to free arginine. The report emphasizes the precursor rather than this terminal conversion, so this node is included as a necessary but less directly specified completion step and should be regarded as modestly speculative in exact natural conditions (Strecker, 1850; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical assembly of ornithine-containing statistical peptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling or peptide aggregation; statistical peptide formation in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentration and condensation convert free ornithine into oligomeric ornithine-containing peptide pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report frames arginine emergence partly through a statistical protein era in which ornithine-containing polypeptides predate arginine-containing ones. This step is included as a connecting biochemical assembly process; exact free-ornithine origins remain uncertain and are therefore not overclaimed here (Longo et al., 2020; Forsythe et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical post-synthetic guanidination of ornithine peptide to arginine peptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"room temperature; neutral to slightly alkaline aqueous solution; statistical side-chain conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The side-chain primary amine of ornithine residues attacks cyanamide, yielding guanidinated arginine residues within the peptide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is directly supported by the supplied report, which describes abiotic aqueous guanidination of ornithine side chains by cyanamide at room temperature and neutral to slightly alkaline pH, with marked improvement in foldability and nucleic-acid binding. This is the strongest non-canonical route to arginine in the research set (Longo et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolytic release of arginine from arginine-containing peptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geothermal or pool hydrolysis; included as network-connecting release step rather than primary natural endpoint\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial peptide hydrolysis liberates free arginine from arginine-containing oligomers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report's main evidence supports peptide guanidination, not necessarily quantitative release of free arginine. This hydrolytic release is therefore included as a necessary network-connecting step and is explicitly secondary to the better-supported peptide endpoint (Longo et al., 2020; Forsythe et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical ornithine to citrulline carbamoylation analogue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"included only as a low-confidence protometabolic analogue; exact prebiotic carbamoyl donor unspecified in supplied report\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbamoyl transfer analogue converts side-chain amine of ornithine to ureido functionality giving citrulline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report discusses citrulline as a biologically central intermediate and mentions formation from ornithine with carbamoyl phosphate in biology, but does not provide a chemically explicit prebiotic route under the supplied evidence. This reaction is therefore marked as speculative and low-confidence, included only to represent the reported protometabolic ornithine/citrulline/arginine conceptual connection (Bada & Lazcano, 2003; as discussed in the supplied review).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical citrulline conversion to arginine analogue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"included only as a speculative protometabolic analogue to reflect literature discussion of urea-cycle-like interconversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amidino-transfer/amination analogue converts citrulline to arginine in a conceptual protometabolic cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied report discusses citrulline as a precursor/intermediate in biological arginine interconversion but does not provide a validated prebiotic chemistry for this step. It is therefore explicitly speculative and included only to reflect the review's mention of a possible protometabolic urea-cycle-like network; it should not be weighted as strongly as the cyanosulfidic or peptide-guanidination routes (as discussed in the supplied review; no direct prebiotic experimental paper specified).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic arginine precursor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct Patel/Sutherland-style route from HCN and acetylene through acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, guanidinated intermediate, hemiaminal 37, cyanohydrin, alpha-hydroxythioamide, thioamide, and arginine alpha-aminonitrile to free arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route with hydrothermal ammonia input\",\n      \"description\": \"Same direct surface route, but explicitly fed by hydrothermal NH3 pool as the nitrogen source coupling vent chemistry to surface photoredox synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route with hydrothermal H2S input\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct surface route emphasizing hydrothermal sulfide delivery into the UV photoredox and sulfidolysis stages.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route emphasizing cyanamide trapping\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct route highlighting cyanamide's dual role in guanidinylation and aldehyde trapping as hemiaminal 37.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Dark-plus-light homologation route to arginine\",\n      \"description\": \"A traversal of the same core chemistry stressing alternation of dark cyanohydrin formation and UV photoredox reductions before hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface integrated arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction and reduced-nitrogen generation feed NH3 and H2S into the surface cyanosulfidic route, giving explicit environmental interconnection before final hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Peptide-first ornithine guanidination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Secondary literature-supported route in which pre-existing ornithine-containing peptides are statistically guanidinated by cyanamide and later hydrolyzed to free arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanamide to peptide-guanylation route\",\n      \"description\": \"A cross-environment route where surface-generated cyanamide is transferred into biochemical pools containing ornithine peptides, yielding arginine peptides and then arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal amino-acid pool to peptide modification route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate/alanine chemistry contributes to a broader amino-acid pool and peptide assembly context, after which ornithine peptide guanidination provides arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative protometabolic ornithine-citrulline-arginine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Low-confidence conceptual pathway included only because the review discusses citrulline and protometabolic urea-cycle-like interconversion; it should be weighted much lower than P1-P9.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_023\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network prioritizes the literature-supported cyanosulfidic synthesis of an arginine alpha-aminonitrile precursor from HCN, acetylene, NH3, H2S, and cyanamide under Cu photoredox/UV conditions in surface geothermal settings, then converts that precursor to free arginine by hydrolysis. Hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively and only where supported by the supplied research: vents provide H2, reduced carbon species, pyruvate, and alanine under Fe-S mineral catalysis, supplying connected feedstocks and environmental interconnection without overclaiming direct arginine assembly at high temperature. A secondary, explicitly downgraded route uses literature-supported post-synthetic guanidination of ornithine residues in peptides by cyanamide, followed by peptide hydrolysis to release arginine; this branch is included as a plausible systems-chemistry entry consistent with the reported ornithine-to-arginine transition but is not treated as the primary route. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated as different valid traversals through the connected network, with HCN, cyanamide, ornithine-containing peptide, arginine alpha-aminonitrile, and arginine as hub/convergence species.", "m